	<http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#wasDerivedFrom> <http://model.geneontology.org/6994852c00002231> ;
	a <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Ontology> ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Edge: AP-2 complex -> AMPAR complex | Relation: constitutively upstream of | PMID: 12441055, 17360429, 24217340 | Model: rat/hippocampal neurons | Perturbation: competing peptides (GluA2-AP2), mut (Stargazin Ser dephosphorylation mutants) | Assay: co-immunoprecipitation, electrophysiology (LTD recording), AMPAR internalization assay | Fig: Lee 2002, Kastning 2007, Matsuda 2013 | Note: AP2 is the constitutive clathrin-cargo adaptor. μ2 subunit directly binds both GluA2/GluA3 and dephosphorylated TARP C-tail, providing dual cargo-recognition mechanism. GluA2-AP2μ2 interaction required for LTD but not constitutive endocytosis. TARP-AP2μ2 interaction enhanced by PP1-mediated dephosphorylation during LTD. AP2 concentrates AMPARs at clathrin-coated pits for internalization."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Node: CACNG2 | UniProt: Q9Y698 | PMID: 15664178 | Model: mouse/cerebrocortical neurons, CHO cells, rat/hippocampal slice culture | Perturbation: none, mut (S9A), mut (S9D), mut (S9D-delta4) | Assay: metabolic labeling, 2D-TLC phosphopeptide mapping, SDS-PAGE mobility shift, Western blot with lambda-phosphatase | Fig: 1A-B, 2A-F | Note: Stargazin phosphorylated on 9 conserved cytoplasmic Ser residues (Ser only, no Thr/Tyr); PSD fraction preferentially phosphorylated; S9A abolishes all phosphorylation; S9D mimics mobility shift; basal phosphorylation half-life ~1 hr (staurosporine, Fig 4A)"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Edge: HPCA -> AP-2 complex | Relation: causally upstream of, positive effect | PMID: 16055064 | Model: rat/hippocampal neurons, rat/hippocampal slices | Perturbation: KD (antisense oligonucleotides), mut (Ca²⁺-binding mutant) | Assay: co-immunoprecipitation, whole-cell patch clamp (LTD recording) | Fig: Palmer 2005 | Note: Hippocalcin forms a Ca²⁺-dependent complex with AP2 and GluA2, bridging Ca²⁺ signaling to AMPAR cargo recognition at endocytic sites. Hippocalcin knockdown blocks hippocampal LTD, indicating it is required for activity-dependent AMPAR recruitment to clathrin-coated pits."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Edge: PPP3CA -> PPP1CA | Relation: positively regulates | PMID: 15664178 | Model: mouse/cerebrocortical neurons | Perturbation: pharmacol (FK506) | Assay: SDS-PAGE mobility shift | Fig: 4G | Note: PP2B acts partly upstream of PP1; FK506 partially blocks NMDA-induced STG dephosphorylation"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Edge: DLG4 -> CACNG2 | Relation: directly positively regulates | PMID: 15664178, 17346965 | Model: rat/hippocampal slice culture, rat/dissociated hippocampal neurons, COS-7 cells | Perturbation: mut (S9D-delta4), mut (ΔC), mut (T321F/H225V compensatory pair) | Assay: paired whole-cell recording, single quantum dot tracking, mEPSC recording, co-clustering in COS-7 | Fig: Tomita 3E, Bats 2B-C, 6B-E, S3, S8 | Note: PSD-95 PDZ domain binding is required for CACNG2's synaptic receptor adaptor activity. Tomita: S9D-delta4 (phosphomimic without PDZ site) depresses AMPA EPSC instead of enhancing it (Fig 3E). Bats: ΔC drops mEPSC frequency from 1.14 to 0.04 Hz (Fig 2B-C); StargazinT321F alone drops AMPAR immobilization to 10%, rescued to 69% by compensatory PSD-95 H225V (Fig 6B); StargazinT321F only localizes to synapses when compensatory PSD-95 is present (Fig S8). PSD-95 turnover (~25% over 5 min) is much slower than Stargazin (~25% in 30s), indicating the Stargazin-PSD-95 dissociation is the rate-limiting step for AMPAR synaptic exit."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Edge: Ca²⁺ -> PICK1 | Relation: is small molecule activator of | PMID: 16107878 | Model: rat/hippocampal neurons, purified recombinant proteins | Perturbation: mut (PICK1 Ca²⁺-binding site mutants) | Assay: co-immunoprecipitation (PICK1-GluA2 binding ± Ca²⁺), AMPAR internalization assay, electrophysiology (LTD recording) | Fig: Hanley & Henley 2005 | Note: Ca²⁺ directly binds PICK1 at acidic N-terminal residues, enhancing PICK1-GluA2 interaction without requiring intermediate enzymatic steps. This allows rapid response to NMDAR-mediated Ca²⁺ influx. Mutation of Ca²⁺-binding site blocks NMDA-stimulated AMPAR internalization and LTD."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Edge: CACNG2 -> GRIA2 | Relation: directly positively regulates | PMID: 17346965 | Model: rat/dissociated hippocampal neurons, COS-7 cells | Perturbation: mut (ΔC, PDZ site deleted), mut (T321F), mut (T321F + H225V rescue) | Assay: single QD tracking, mEPSC recording, co-clustering in COS-7 | Fig: Bats 3F-J, 5A-F, 6A-E, 8A-C, S3 | Note: ΔC reduces GluR2 immobile fraction from 52% to 26% and confined time from 68% to 44% (Fig 3H-J). StargazinT321F alone drops immobilization to 10%; rescued to 69% by compensatory PSD-95 H225V (Fig 6B). FRAP crosslinking of GluR2 also immobilizes Stargazin, proving they diffuse as a complex in both synaptic and extrasynaptic membrane (Fig 8A-C). Importantly, GluR2 ΔC (lacking its own PDZ site) does NOT change lateral diffusion (Fig 5C-F), demonstrating synaptic trapping depends on Stargazin, not GluR2 C-terminus."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Node: HPCA | UniProt: P84074 | PMID: 16055064 | Model: rat/hippocampal neurons, rat/hippocampal slices | Perturbation: KD (antisense oligonucleotides), mut (hippocalcin Ca²⁺-binding mutant) | Assay: co-immunoprecipitation, whole-cell patch clamp (LTD recording) | Fig: Palmer 2005 | Note: Hippocalcin is a neuronal Ca²⁺ sensor that forms a Ca²⁺-dependent complex with AP2 and GluA2. Hippocalcin knockdown or Ca²⁺-binding mutation blocks hippocampal LTD, indicating it bridges AP2-GluA2 interaction in response to NMDAR-mediated Ca²⁺ signals."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , """Edge: PPP1CA -> CACNG2 | Relation: directly negatively regulates | PMID: 15664178 | Model: mouse/cerebrocortical neurons | Perturbation: tautomycin (10 μM, PP1 inhibitor), FK506 (1 μM, PP2B inhibitor), EGTA (5 mM), NMDA (20 μM), staurosporine (1 μM) | Assay: SDS-PAGE mobility shift (stargazin phosphorylation state), ³²P-orthophosphate stripping | Fig: Tomita 2005 Fig 4B (tautomycin completely blocks basal dephosphorylation), Fig 4E (NMDA strips ³²P from stargazin), Fig 4F (tautomycin blocks NMDA-induced dephosphorylation), Fig 4G (tautomycin blocks, FK506 partly blocks) | Note: PP1 dephosphorylates the 9 conserved serine residues on Stargazin's C-terminal tail, shifting it to lower apparent molecular weight on SDS-PAGE. Tautomycin (PP1 inhibitor) completely blocks both basal dephosphorylation (Fig 4B) and NMDA-induced dephosphorylation (Fig 4F-G). This dephosphorylation is Ca²⁺-dependent (blocked by EGTA, Fig 4F) and partly downstream of PP2B/calcineurin (partially blocked by FK506, Fig 4G). The functional consequence is that dephosphorylated Stargazin loses synaptic AMPAR anchoring — the S9D phosphomimic blocks LTD (Fig 4H), confirming that PP1-mediated dephosphorylation of Stargazin is required for LTD expression.
ECO: ECO:0006054 (pharmacological loss-of-function — tautomycin blocks dephosphorylation, Fig 4B + 4F-G) + ECO:0001096 (SDS-PAGE mobility shift — stargazin band shift, Fig 4A-G)"""^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Node: PRKCA | UniProt: P17252 | PMID: 15664178 | Model: purified recombinant proteins, mouse/cerebrocortical neurons | Perturbation: none, pharmacol (GF109203X) | Assay: in vitro kinase assay, SDS-PAGE mobility shift | Fig: 5B-C | Note: PKC directly phosphorylates STG tail more efficiently than histone; GF109203X blocks STG rephosphorylation in neurons after NMDA washout"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Edge: IQSEC1 -> ARF6 | Relation: directly positively regulates | PMID: 20510858 | Model: purified recombinant proteins, HEK293 cells (transfected), rat/hippocampal neuron cultures | Perturbation: mut (E604K catalytically inactive), KD (lentiviral RNAi), pharmacol (PP2 src inhibitor, OV/PAO tyrosine phosphatase inhibitors) | Assay: in vitro nucleotide exchange assay, Arf6-GTP pull-down (cellular) | Fig: 3A-D, 4A-C, 5C-D | Note: GluA2-CT stimulates BRAG2 GEF activity on Arf6 ~5-fold in vitro; this stimulation requires intact 3Y motif and unphosphorylated Y876 (Fig 3A-D). In HEK293 cells, glutamate and CNQX (partial agonist) both trigger BRAG2-dependent Arf6 activation (Fig 4A-B). In neurons, DHPG activates Arf6 via tyrosine dephosphorylation; this is blocked by BRAG2 RNAi and by tyrosine phosphatase inhibitors OV/PAO (Fig 5C-D). Src inhibitor PP2 alone activates Arf6 by releasing Y876 phosphorylation brake (Fig 4C)."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Node: GRIP1 | UniProt: Q9Y3R0 | PMID: 11953746 | Model: KIF5b-knockout mouse primary extra-embryonic cells, mouse brain lysates, cultured rat brain neurons | Perturbation: KIF5b gene knockout, dominant negative KIF5A expression (GFP-KHCCBD) | Assay: yeast two-hybrid, co-immunoprecipitation, subcellular fractionation, fluorescence microscopy | Fig: 1b, 1c, 2e, 3e, 4a-d | Note: GRIP1 functions as a synaptic receptor adaptor and scaffolding protein that directly binds kinesin heavy chains (KIF5). By forming a complex with AMPA receptor subunits (GluR2), GRIP1 acts as the steering mechanism that directs the kinesin motor protein to drive transport toward the somatodendritic compartment rather than the axon."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , """Edge: NSF -> PICK1 | Relation: directly negatively regulates | PMID: 11931741 | Model: purified recombinant proteins (his6NSF, GST-PICK1, his6mycR2C, his6α/β-SNAP), rat/hippocampal extract (co-IP), rat/hippocampal neurons (Sindbis overexpression) | Perturbation: ATPγS trapping vs ATP hydrolysis, α-SNAP vs β-SNAP titration, GluR2 C-terminal mutants (-SVKI, -AVKI, -SVKE) | Assay: in vitro disassembly assay (GST pull-down + ATP/ATPγS), co-IP from hippocampal lysate, acid-strip endocytosis assay, surface immunostaining | Fig: Hanley 2002 Fig 4A (disassembly — lane 6 ATPγS stable, lane 14 ATP+αSNAP disassembles, lane 15 ATP+βSNAP stabilizes), Fig 4B-C (NSF and SNAP dose-response), Fig 4D-E (hippocampal co-IP confirms complex in vivo, ATP-sensitive), Fig 5A-B (α-SNAP overexpression increases surface GluR1 50%), Fig 6A-B (β-SNAP overexpression enhances AMPAR endocytosis 4-fold), Fig 6E-F (effect requires PICK1-binding GluR2, not -SVKE mutant) | Note: NSF ATPase activity disrupts the GluR2-PICK1 complex in the presence of α-SNAP, releasing R2C, PICK1, NSF and α-SNAP from the complex (Fig 4A lane 14). β-SNAP at low concentrations stimulates but at high concentrations inhibits this disassembly (Fig 4Cii). This was confirmed in vivo: co-IP from hippocampus shows GluR2 dissociates from PICK1 in MgATP but not ATPγS (Fig 4D-E). β-SNAP overexpression in neurons enhances AMPAR endocytosis 4-fold specifically via GluR2-PICK1 complexes (Fig 6E-F).
ECO: ECO:0000005 (in vitro enzymatic/disassembly assay, Fig 4A) + ECO:0000070 (co-IP from hippocampus, Fig 4D) + ECO:0005027 (immunocytochemistry in neurons, Fig 5-6)"""^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Node: PICK1 | UniProt: Q9NRD5 | PMID: 28855251, 16107878 | Model: rat/cortical neurons, rat/hippocampal neurons, HEK293 cells, dynamin TKO fibroblasts, purified recombinant proteins | Perturbation: KD (shRNA), mut (DDAA — D189A/D356A, AP2-binding dead), mut (K27E, GluA2-binding dead), mut (D189A single), pharmacol (cyclosporin A, FK506 — calcineurin inhibitors) | Assay: co-immunoprecipitation, GST pull-down, surface biotinylation, antibody-feeding internalization assay, STED super-resolution imaging, spinning-disk confocal live imaging, dynamin polymerization sedimentation assay | Fig: Fiuza 1A-B, 2B-D, 3A-C, 4A-F, 5A-C, 6A-E, 7A-D | Note: PICK1 is a BAR domain protein that binds GluA2 C-terminus via its PDZ domain (enhanced directly by Ca²⁺; Hanley & Henley 2005) and binds AP2 α-appendage via FxDxF/DxF motifs (enhanced by calcineurin after NMDAR stimulation; Fiuza Fig 5B-C). PICK1 colocalizes with clathrin clusters at endocytic zones in dendrites (STED, Fig 1B) and is recruited to CCPs in an AP2-dependent, dynamin-independent manner (dynamin TKO fibroblasts, Fig 3A-C). DDAA mutation abolishes AP2 binding and blocks both constitutive and NMDA-stimulated AMPAR internalization (Fig 7A-C). PICK1-GluA2 binding peaks earlier than PICK1-AP2 binding after NMDAR stimulation; AP2 binding to PICK1 competitively displaces GluA2 (Fig 6A-E), suggesting PICK1 hands off cargo to AP2 at endocytic sites."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Node: NSF | UniProt: P46460 | PMID: 10571232, 11931741, 17302911 | Model: rat/hippocampal slice (electrophysiology), purified recombinant proteins (his6NSF, GST-R2C, his6flagPICK1, his6α/β-SNAP), rat/hippocampal neurons (immunocytochemistry) | Perturbation: competing peptides (pep2m, pep-R845A, pep-ΔA849-Q853), ATPγS vs ATP, D142A Ca²⁺-binding mutant, α/β-SNAP overexpression | Assay: whole-cell patch clamp + dendritic minimal stimulation (EPSC rundown + LTD occlusion), in vitro disassembly assay (GST pull-down + ATP/ATPγS), ⁴⁵Ca²⁺ equilibrium dialysis, acid-strip endocytosis assay, surface immunostaining | Fig: Lüthi 1999 Fig 1-2 (rundown + occlusion), Fig 8 (pep2m vs LTD comparison); Hanley 2002 Fig 4A (disassembly, lane 14 vs 15), Fig 4D-E (hippocampal co-IP), Fig 5-6 (SNAP overexpression surface + endocytosis); Hanley 2007 Fig 1a (Ca²⁺-sensitive NSF-R2C binding), Fig 2a-c (⁴⁵Ca²⁺ binding + R2C competition), Fig 3 (D142A mutant) | Note: NSF is a hexameric ATPase that dissociates PICK1 from GluA2 in an ATP-dependent manner requiring α-SNAP as cofactor (Hanley et al. 2002, Fig 4A lane 14). NSF directly binds Ca²⁺ (Kd ~15.7 μM), and 15 μM Ca²⁺ reduces NSF-GluR2 binding to ~45% (Hanley 2007, Fig 1a, 2a). This means during NMDAR-mediated Ca²⁺ influx, NSF releases from GluA2, allowing PICK1 to remain bound and promote internalization. Disrupting GluA2-NSF with pep2m causes EPSC rundown that mutually occludes LTD (Lüthi et al. 1999, Fig 1-2)."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Edge: ARF6 -> AP-2 complex | Relation: causally upstream of, positive effect | PMID: 20510858, 12835311 | Model: rat/hippocampal neurons, rat synaptosomes | Perturbation: mut (Arf6-T44N constitutively inactive) | Assay: Arf6-GTP pull-down, surface biotinylation, PI(4,5)P2 measurement | Fig: Scholz 6D, Krauss 2003 | Note: Active Arf6-GTP recruits phosphatidylinositol 4-phosphate 5-kinase type Iγ to the plasma membrane, locally increasing PI(4,5)P2 concentration (Krauss et al. 2003). AP2 has high affinity for PI(4,5)P2 and clusters at PI(4,5)P2-rich membrane domains. Arf6-GTP also directly binds AP2 (Paleotti et al. 2005). Together this creates a local environment favorable for CCP formation near ligand-bound, dephosphorylated AMPARs."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Node: ARF6 | UniProt: P62330 | PMID: 20510858 | Model: HEK293 cells (transfected), rat/hippocampal neuron cultures | Perturbation: mut (Arf6-T44N, constitutively inactive) | Assay: Arf6-GTP pull-down, surface biotinylation | Fig: Scholz 4A-C, 6D | Note: Arf6 is a small GTPase activated by BRAG2 at the plasma membrane. Active Arf6-GTP recruits PI(4,5)P2 kinases to locally increase PI(4,5)P2 concentration, creating a landing pad for AP2 clustering at nascent clathrin-coated pits near AMPARs. Constitutively inactive Arf6-T44N blocks DHPG-induced surface GluA2 reduction (Scholz Fig 6D)."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Node: CAMK2A | UniProt: Q9UQM7 | PMID: 15664178 | Model: purified recombinant proteins, mouse/cerebrocortical neurons | Perturbation: none, pharmacol (KN93) | Assay: in vitro kinase assay, SDS-PAGE mobility shift | Fig: 5B-C | Note: CaMKII directly phosphorylates purified STG C-terminal tail with efficiency comparable to GluR1 tail; KN93 blocks STG rephosphorylation in neurons after NMDA washout"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Edge: CACNG2 -> GRIA1 | Relation: directly positively regulates | PMID: 15664178, 17346965 | Model: Xenopus oocytes, rat/hippocampal slice culture, rat/dissociated hippocampal neurons | Perturbation: mut (S9A), mut (S9D), mut (S9D-delta4), mut (ΔC, PDZ site deleted), mut (T321F) | Assay: two-electrode voltage clamp, paired whole-cell recording, outside-out patch, single QD tracking, mEPSC recording | Fig: Tomita 3A-E, Bats 1A-E, 2A-E, 3A-E, 4A-D | Note: Tomita: S9D enhances synaptic AMPA currents (Fig 3D); S9A does not (Fig 3C); S9DΔ4 depresses them (Fig 3E); surface trafficking unaffected by phosphorylation state (Fig 3A-B). Bats: AMPARs are reversibly trapped on PSD-95 clusters via Stargazin (immobile fraction 25% to 82%, Fig 1D); ΔC reduces GluR1 immobile fraction from 52% to 16% (Fig 3C) and synaptic dwell time from 15s to 4.9s (Fig 4C). Stargazin and GluR1-AMPARs diffuse as complexes (Fig 8)."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Node: Calcineurin complex | has part: PPP3CB, PPP3R1, PPP3CA | PMID: 7516487, 28855251 | Model: rat/hippocampal slices, rat/hippocampal neurons | Perturbation: pharmacol (FK506, cyclosporin A) | Assay: electrophysiology (LTD recording), co-immunoprecipitation (PICK1-AP2 binding) | Fig: Mulkey 1994, Fiuza 2017 Fig 5C | Note: Calcineurin (PP2B) is a Ca²⁺-dependent phosphatase with a well-established role in hippocampal LTD. FK506/cyclosporin A block LTD expression (Mulkey 1994). In the context of AMPAR endocytosis, calcineurin activity is required for the NMDAR-dependent increase in PICK1-AP2 and PICK1-dynamin binding (Fiuza 2017 Fig 5C). Calcineurin also acts partly upstream of PP1 in mediating NMDA-induced Stargazin dephosphorylation (Tomita 2005 Fig 4G)."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Node: IQSEC1 | UniProt: Q6DN90 | PMID: 20510858 | Model: yeast two-hybrid, HEK293 cells (transfected), rat/hippocampal neuron cultures, mouse/hippocampal slices (acute, in vivo lentiviral injection), Iqsec1fl/fl conditional KO mice, purified recombinant proteins | Perturbation: KD (lentiviral RNAi, two independent shRNAs), KO (Cre-lox conditional, Iqsec1fl/fl), mut (E604K catalytically inactive), competing peptide (GST-3Y vs GST-3Y-V875Y/Y876V) | Assay: yeast two-hybrid, GST pull-down, co-immunoprecipitation, in vitro nucleotide exchange assay, Arf6-GTP pull-down (cellular), surface biotinylation, cell ELISA, reversible surface biotinylation (endocytosis), whole-cell patch clamp (LTD recording), subcellular fractionation, Western blot | Fig: 1A-E, 2A-C, 3A-D, 4A-C, 5A-D, 6A-F, 7A-C, 8A-B | Note: BRAG2 is a synaptic Arf6-GEF concentrated in PSD fractions that directly binds GluA2 via the 3Y motif (YKEGYNVY876G) through its Sec7-PH module (Y2H, GST pull-down, co-IP; Fig 1A-E). GluA2 C-terminus stimulates BRAG2 GEF activity ~5-fold in vitro, controlled by Y876 phosphorylation state — dephosphorylated Y876 permits activation, phosphorylation blocks it (Fig 3A-D). AMPAR ligand binding (glutamate or CNQX) triggers BRAG2-dependent Arf6 activation in HEK293 cells and neurons (Fig 4A-C). BRAG2 is required for both mGluR-LTD and NMDAR-LTD — RNAi, conditional KO, catalytically inactive mutant, and competing 3Y peptide all block LTD expression without affecting initial DHPG-induced depression (Fig 6A-F, 7A-C, 8A-B)."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Edge: Calcineurin -> PICK1 | Relation: directly positively regulates | PMID: 28855251 | Model: rat/cortical neurons, rat/hippocampal neurons, HEK293 cells | Perturbation: pharmacol (cyclosporin A, FK506), OE (constitutively active calcineurin vs. phosphatase-dead calcineurin) | Assay: co-immunoprecipitation (PICK1-AP2 binding ± calcineurin inhibitors), PICK1-AP2 binding in HEK293 with CA/PD calcineurin | Fig: Fiuza 5B-C, S4A-B | Note: NMDAR-dependent increase in PICK1-AP2α and PICK1-dynamin binding requires calcineurin activity. Cyclosporin A and FK506 both block the NMDA-stimulated increase. Constitutively active calcineurin enhances PICK1-AP2 binding in HEK293 cells; phosphatase-dead calcineurin does not. The calcineurin substrate in this mechanism is unknown."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , """
Node: AP-2 adaptor complex | has part: AP2A2, AP2M1 | PMID: 12441055, 17360429, 24217340, 28855251 | Model: rat/hippocampal neurons, purified recombinant proteins | Perturbation: competing peptides (GluA2-AP2 interaction), mut (Stargazin Ser dephosphorylation mutants), mut (PICK1 DDAA) | Assay: co-immunoprecipitation, GST pull-down, electrophysiology (LTD recording), clathrin cluster recruitment imaging | Fig: Lee 2002, Kastning 2007, Matsuda 2013, Fiuza 2017 Fig 6B | Note: AP2 is the core endocytic adaptor that clusters at PI(4,5)P2-rich membrane domains and recruits cargo to clathrin-coated pits. μ2 subunit directly binds both GluA2/GluA3 (required for LTD but not constitutive endocytosis; Lee 2002, Kastning 2007) and dephosphorylated Stargazin C-tail (Matsuda 2013). α-appendage binds PICK1 via FxDxF/DxF motifs (Fiuza 2017). These three cargo-recognition interactions converge to recruit AMPARs to CCPs during LTD."""^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Edge: ATAD1 -> GRIP1 | Relation: ATAD1 negatively regulates the GRIP1-GluR2 complex by directly mediating its disassembly | PMID: 21496646 | Model: Mus musculus, HEK293 cells | Perturbation: ATP vs. ATPγS addition (hydrolyzable vs. non-hydrolyzable ATP) | Assay: Co-immunoprecipitation, GST-pull down, in vitro complex disassembly assay | Fig: 1, 5 | Note: Thorase physically interacts with both the C-terminus of the GluR2 AMPAR subunit and the PDZ5 domain of GRIP1. In the presence of hydrolyzable ATP, Thorase provides the driving mechanical force to disrupt and disassemble the GRIP1-GluR2 complex, an essential step that allows AMPAR internalization to proceed."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Edge: PICK1 -> AP-2 complex | Relation: provides input for | PMID: 28855251 | Model: rat/hippocampal neurons, dynamin TKO fibroblasts, purified recombinant proteins | Perturbation: mut (DDAA — AP2-binding dead), mut (K27E — GluA2-binding dead), KD (PICK1 shRNA) | Assay: co-immunoprecipitation, GST pull-down, STED imaging (PICK1-clathrin colocalization), surface GluA2-clathrin colocalization imaging, surface biotinylation, antibody-feeding internalization assay | Fig: Fiuza 2B-D, 5A, 6B, 7A-C | Note: PICK1 binds AP2 α-appendage via FxDxF (D189) and DxF (D356) motifs. DDAA mutation abolishes AP2 binding and blocks NMDAR-dependent recruitment of surface GluA2 to clathrin clusters (Fig 6B). Both PICK1-GluA2 (K27E) and PICK1-AP2 (DDAA) interactions are required for clustering AMPARs at endocytic zones. AP2 binding to PICK1 competitively displaces GluA2 from PICK1 PDZ domain (Fig 6C-E), suggesting PICK1 delivers GluA2 cargo to AP2 and then releases it for direct AP2μ2-GluA2 engagement."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Node: PPP3CA | UniProt: Q08209 | PMID: 15664178 | Model: mouse/cerebrocortical neurons | Perturbation: pharmacol (FK506) | Assay: SDS-PAGE mobility shift | Fig: 4A,4G | Note: PP2B partially blocks NMDA-induced STG dephosphorylation; acts partly upstream of PP1"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , """Edge: Ca²⁺ -> NSF | Relation: is small molecule inhibitor of | PMID: 17302911 | Model: purified recombinant proteins (his6NSF, GST-R2C) | Perturbation: D142A NSF Ca²⁺-binding mutant | Assay: GST pull-down at varying [Ca²⁺]free, ⁴⁵Ca²⁺ equilibrium dialysis | Fig: Hanley 2007 Fig 1a (Ca²⁺ inhibits NSF-R2C binding, p<0.001 at 15 μM), Fig 2a (NSF binds Ca²⁺, Kd=15.7 μM), Fig 2c (R2C competes with Ca²⁺ for NSF binding), Fig 3a-b (D142A reduces Ca²⁺ affinity to 34.5 μM and abolishes Ca²⁺ sensitivity of R2C binding) | Note: Ca²⁺ directly binds NSF (~1 ion per hexamer) and reduces NSF-GluR2 interaction to ~45% at 15 μM. R2C and Ca²⁺ compete for binding to NSF, suggesting overlapping binding sites. The D142A mutant confirms Ca²⁺ binding to NSF mediates this effect, not Ca²⁺ binding to GluR2.
ECO: ECO:0000002 (direct binding assay — ⁴⁵Ca²⁺ equilibrium dialysis, Fig 2a) + ECO:0006054 (loss-of-function mutant D142A, Fig 3a-b)"""^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Edge: PRKCA -> CACNG2 | Relation: directly positively regulates | PMID: 15664178 | Model: purified recombinant proteins, mouse/cerebrocortical neurons | Perturbation: none (in vitro), pharmacol (GF109203X, cellular) | Assay: in vitro kinase assay (direct), SDS-PAGE mobility shift (cellular) | Fig: 5B-C | Note: Direct phosphorylation of STG tail in vitro (more efficient than histone); confirmed in neurons where GF109203X blocks rephosphorylation after NMDA washout"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Edge: CAMK2A -> CACNG2 | Relation: directly positively regulates | PMID: 15664178 | Model: purified recombinant proteins, mouse/cerebrocortical neurons | Perturbation: none (in vitro), pharmacol (KN93, cellular) | Assay: in vitro kinase assay (direct), SDS-PAGE mobility shift (cellular) | Fig: 5B-C | Note: Direct phosphorylation of STG tail in vitro; confirmed in neurons where KN93 blocks rephosphorylation after NMDA washout"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Node: ATAD1 | UniProt: Q8NBU5 | PMID: 21496646 | Model: Mus musculus, primary mouse hippocampal neurons, primary mouse cortical neurons, HEK293 cells | Perturbation: Knockout (conditional genetic deletion), overexpression (lentiviral transduction), missense mutations (Walker A K193T, Walker B E139Q), TTX treatment, bicuculline treatment | Assay: Immunoblot, subcellular fractionation, co-immunoprecipitation, GST-pull down, surface biotinylation, live-cell immunohistochemistry, whole-cell patch-clamp, behavioral assays | Fig: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7 | Note: Thorase (ATAD1) is a postsynaptically enriched AAA+ ATPase that regulates synaptic plasticity, learning, and memory. It critically controls the surface expression and endocytosis of AMPA receptors (AMPARs) through an ATPase-dependent mechanism, where its deletion leads to increased surface AMPAR levels, enhanced LTP, eliminated LTD, and severe behavioral deficits."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "dge: GRIP1 -> GRIA2 | Relation: directly positively regulates | PMID: 11953746 | Model: mouse brain subcellular fractions, cultured rat brain neurons | Perturbation: dominant negative KIF5A expression (GFP-KHCCBD) | Assay: co-immunoprecipitation, fluorescence microscopy | Fig: 2e, 3b, 3c, 3e | Note: GRIP1 physically links the AMPA receptor subunit GRIA2 to KIF5 motor proteins to form a functional dendritic transport complex. Competitive disruption of the GRIP1-kinesin interaction using a dominant negative kinesin construct prevents both GRIP1 and GRIA2 from properly localizing to dendritic synapses."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , "Node: DLG4 | UniProt: P78352 | PMID: 15664178, 17346965 | Model: rat/hippocampal slice culture, rat/dissociated hippocampal neurons | Perturbation: mut (S9D-delta4, phosphomimic lacking PDZ site), mut (ΔC, PDZ site deleted), mut (T321F/H225V compensatory pair) | Assay: paired whole-cell recording, single quantum dot tracking, mEPSC recording | Fig: Tomita 3E, Bats 1D-E, 2B-C, 6B-E, 7A-C | Note: PSD-95 clusters reversibly trap AMPARs (immobile fraction 25% to 82%, diffusion drops to 0.007 μm²/s on clusters; Bats Fig 1D-E). Stargazin is trapped on PSD-95 clusters to the same extent as AMPARs (Bats Fig 7). S9D-delta4 lacking PDZ site depresses AMPA EPSC, showing PSD-95 interaction is required for phosphorylated STG synaptic function (Tomita Fig 3E). Compensatory T321F/H225V pair rescues AMPAR immobilization from 10% to 69% (Bats Fig 6B), confirming specificity of the Stargazin-PSD-95 interaction."^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , """
Node: AMPA glutamate receptor complex | has part: GRIA2, GRIA1, CACNG2 | PMID: standard GO annotation | Note: The cargo being endocytosed. GluA2-containing AMPARs are the predominant synaptic AMPAR species in mature hippocampal CA1 neurons. Subunit composition determines which adaptor interactions are available (GluA2 binds AP2 μ2, BRAG2, GRIP, PICK1, NSF; GluA1 does not bind AP2 μ2)."""^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> , """Node: PPP1CA | UniProt: P62137 | PMID: 15664178, 7724573 | Model: mouse/cerebrocortical neurons (pharmacology, ³²P labeling), rat/neostriatum (immunocytochemistry) | Perturbation: tautomycin (PP1 inhibitor), FK506 (PP2B inhibitor), okadaic acid (PP2A inhibitor), staurosporine (broad kinase inhibitor) | Assay: SDS-PAGE mobility shift (stargazin phosphorylation state), ³²P-orthophosphate metabolic labeling, immunoelectron microscopy | Fig: Tomita 2005 Fig 4A (staurosporine dephosphorylation), Fig 4B (tautomycin blocks dephosphorylation), Fig 4F-G (tautomycin blocks NMDA-induced dephosphorylation); Ouimet 1995 Fig 1-3 (PP1 concentrated in dendritic spines) | Note: PP1 mediates both basal and NMDA-induced dephosphorylation of stargazin. Tautomycin (PP1 inhibitor) completely blocks stargazin dephosphorylation in cortical neurons, while FK506 (PP2B inhibitor) partially blocks it, indicating PP1 acts downstream of calcineurin (Tomita et al. 2005, Fig 4B, 4F-G). PP1α and PP1γ1 are highly concentrated in dendritic spines (Ouimet et al. 1995, Fig 3A-B), placing PP1 in the correct subcellular compartment to act on postsynaptic substrates including Stargazin.
MF: protein serine/threonine phosphatase activity (GO:0004722)
has input: CACNG2 (Stargazin) — pharmacological evidence: tautomycin blocks stargazin dephosphorylation (Tomita 2005 Fig 4B, 4F)
BP: protein dephosphorylation (GO:0006470)
CC: postsynaptic density (GO:0014069) — Ouimet 1995 Fig 3A (EM: PP1 in dendritic spine heads and PSDs)
ECO for MF: ECO:0000112 (Western/SDS-PAGE mobility shift evidence — stargazin mobility shift, Fig 4A-B) + ECO:0005027 (immunoelectron microscopy — PP1 in spines, Ouimet Fig 3)
"""^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string> ;
